05184nam a22006975i 9780691186757DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911867577 a10.1515/97806911867572doi  a(DE-B1597)501946  a(OCoLC)1076451574  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQC173.6b.E4213 2006eb 7aSCI0340002bisacsh04a530.112221 aEisenstaedt, Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Curious History of Relativity :bHow Einstein's Theory of Gravity Was Lost and Found Again /cJean Eisenstaedt. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. A Difficult Theory -- tCHAPTER ONE. The Speed of Light and Classical Physics -- tCHAPTER TWO. Light and the Structure of Space-Time -- tCHAPTER THREE. Toward a New Theory of Gravitation -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Einstein's Principles -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Birth of General Relativity -- tCHAPTER SIX. General Relativity: A Physical Geometry -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Relativity Verified: Mercury's Anomaly -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Relativity Verified: The Deflection of Light Rays -- tCHAPTER NINE. Relativity Verified: The Line Shift -- tCHAPTER TEN. The Crossing of the Desert -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN. An Unpopular Theory -- tCHAPTER TWELVE. The Rejection of Black Holes -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN. Paths in Schwarzschild's Space-Time -- tCHAPTER FOURTEEN. No Ordinary Stars -- tCHAPTER FIFTEEN. Gravitation, Astrophysics, and Cosmology -- tAFTERWORD. The Paths of General Relativity -- tBibliography -- tName Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBlack holes may obliterate most things that come near them, but they saved the theory of general relativity. Einstein's theory was quickly accepted as the true theory of gravity after its publication in 1915, but soon took a back seat in physics to quantum mechanics and languished for decades on the blackboards of mathematicians. Not until the existence of black holes by Stephen Hawking and Roger Penrose in the 1960s, after Einstein's death, was the theory revived. Almost one hundred years after general relativity replaced Newton's theory of gravitation, The Curious History of Relativity tells the story of both events surrounding general relativity and the techniques employed by Einstein and the relativists to construct, develop, and understand his almost impenetrable theory. Jean Eisenstaedt, one of the world's leading experts on the subject, also discusses the theory's place in the evolution of twentieth-century physics. He describes the main stages in the development of general relativity: its beginnings, its strange crossing of the desert during Einstein's lifetime while under heated criticism, and its new life from the 1960s on, when it became vital to the understanding of black holes and the observation of exotic objects, and, eventually, to the discovery of the accelerating universe. We witness Einstein's construction of his theory, as well as the work of his fascinated, discouraged, and enthusiastic colleagues--physicists, mathematicians, and astronomers. Written with flair, The Curious History of Relativity poses--and answers--the difficult questions raised by Einstein's magnificent intellectual feat.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGeneral relativity (Physics). 0aSpace and time. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh1 aDamour, Thibault, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/97806911867